ce:section.ce:para:
The PCDs were prepared from phosphoric acid and m-phenylenediamine via an ethanol solvothermal treatment, as described in our previous work. The TEM images reveal that the PCDs exhibit a narrow size distribution with an average diameter of 4–5 nm. The HR-TEM image of the PCDs reveals a distinct fringe spacing of 0.21 nm, which corresponds to the (100) facet of graphite [44] (Fig. S1). The XPS spectra of PCDs confirm the incorporation of the P element into the carbon dots, The atomic percentages of C, N, O, and P are 50.66 %, 6.2 %, 36.65 %, and 6.49 % in PCDs, respectively (Fig. S2a). And for the FTIR spectra of PCDs (Fig. S2b), the new absorption peaks at 967 cm−1 and 1050 cm−1 were assigned to the stretching vibration of PN and CO/ PO. Furthermore, the photoluminescence excitation-emission spectra of PCDs and BCDs aqueous solutions (Fig. S3) reveal that the doping of P element changes the luminescent bandgaps of the CDs. The PCD@BA composite was obtained by annealing a mixture of PCDs and BA in an aqueous solution (as shown in Scheme 1
                        ). The resulting powder effectively prevents aggregation-induced quenching and exhibits photoluminescent properties in the solid state. The absorption spectra of the PCD@BA were measured and presented in Fig. S4, demonstrating a broader absorption band from UV to visible light. Fig. 1
                        a presents the photoluminescence excitation-emission spectra of the PCD@BA composite, showing a broad fluorescence band in the 400–600 nm range, with the emission peak centered approximately at 510–540 nm. The fluorescence emission of the PCD@BA composite also exhibits no significant excitation dependence. The photoluminescence excitation-emission spectra of the BCD@BA composite were shown in Fig. S5, revealing a narrower emission centered in the cyan region under 350–360 nm excitation. The PLQY of the PCD@BA composite was measured to be 22.7 %, significantly surpassing that of BCD@BA, which was 8 % (as shown in Fig. S6). The results of the photoluminescence excitation-emission spectra demonstrate that P-doping in CDs induces further significant changes in the emission of the composite system. The PCD@BA composite also exhibits a bright long-lifetime afterglow under UV or visible light excitation (as shown in Fig. 1b). Upon turning off the 295 nm light, a cyan afterglow emission is observable for at least 22 s. Additionally, a green afterglow signal from PCD@BA can be activated by white light from a mobile phone flashlight, lasting up to 6 s under naked-eye observation. Then, the afterglow spectra of the PCD@BA composite under various excitation wavelengths (254 nm, 290 nm, 360 nm, and 450 nm) were measured and are presented in Fig. 1c. The main emission peak is centered at approximately 535 nm, indicating both a redshift and a significant enhancement in intensity compared to the BCD@BA composite (Fig. S7). No afterglow signal was observed in the PCD powders, which further confirms the photoluminescence quenching in the PCD solid powders (Fig. S8). Notably, the green afterglow emission peaked at 535 nm in PCD@BA composite, which can be effectively excited by both UV and visible light. A blue afterglow emission peaked at 450 nm and also could be observed under UV light excitation. The properties of visible-light excited afterglow emission were further investigated through the afterglow excitation spectrum of the PCD@BA composite (measured at 535 nm). As shown in Fig. 1d, the excitation peaks were observed in both the UV and visible light regions. Based on the afterglow emission spectra, the time-resolved afterglow decay curves of the PCD@BA composite (measured at 450 and 535 nm) were also recorded and shown in Fig. 1e and Fig. S9. These decay curves could be fitted with a triexponential function, the average afterglow lifetime of the PCD@BA composite at 450 nm was found to be 1.41 s (excited at 290 nm) and 1.26 s (excited at 365 nm), while the average lifetimes at 535 nm were calculated to be 0.86 s (excited at 290 nm), 405 ms (excited at 365 nm) and 196 ms (excited at 450 nm), respectively.
